aa(lp83
VNow, when I started looking into collective action,
p84
aVthe considerable literature on it is based on what sociologists call "social dilemmas."
p85
aVAnd there are a couple of mythic narratives of social dilemmas.
p86
aVI'm going to talk briefly about two of them:
p87
aVthe prisoner's dilemma and the tragedy of the commons.
p88
aa(lp89
VNow, when I talked about this with Kevin Kelly,
p90
aVhe assured me that everybody in this audience pretty much knows the details
p91
aVof the prisoner's dilemma,
p92
aVso I'm just going to go over that very, very quickly.
p93
aVIf you have more questions about it, ask Kevin Kelly later. (Laughter)
p94
aa(lp95
VThe prisoner's dilemma is actually a story that's overlaid
p96
aVon a mathematical matrix that came out of the game theory
p97
aVin the early years of thinking about nuclear war:
p98
aVtwo players who couldn't trust each other.
p99
aVLet me just say that every unsecured transaction
p100
aVis a good example of a prisoner's dilemma.
p101
aVPerson with the goods, person with the money,
p102
aVbecause they can't trust each other, are not going to exchange.
p103
aVNeither one wants to be the first one
p104
aVor they're going to get the sucker's payoff,
p105
aVbut both lose, of course, because they don't get what they want.
p106
aVIf they could only agree, if they could only turn a prisoner's dilemma into
p107
aVa different payoff matrix called an assurance game, they could proceed.
p108
aa(lp109
VTwenty years ago, Robert Axelrod used the prisoner's dilemma
p110
aVas a probe of the biological question:
p111
aVif we are here because our ancestors were such fierce competitors,
p112
aVhow does cooperation exist at all?
p113
aVHe started a computer tournament for
p114
aVpeople to submit prisoner's dilemma strategies and discovered,
p115
aVmuch to his surprise, that a very, very simple strategy won \u2014
p116
aVit won the first tournament, and even after everyone knew it won,
p117
aVit won the second tournament \u2014 that's known as tit for tat.
p118
aa(lp119
VAnother economic game that may not be as well known as the prisoner's dilemma
p120
aVis the ultimatum game,
p121
aVand it's also a very interesting probe of
p122
aVour assumptions about the way people make economic transactions.
p123
aVHere's how the game is played: there are two players;
p124
aVthey've never played the game before,
p125
aVthey will not play the game again, they don't know each other,
p126
aVand they are, in fact, in separate rooms.
p127
aVFirst player is offered a hundred dollars
p128
aVand is asked to propose a split: 50/50, 90/10,
p129
aVwhatever that player wants to propose. The second player either accepts the split \u2014
p130
aVboth players are paid and the game is over \u2014
p131
aVor rejects the split \u2014 neither player is paid and the game is over.
p132
aa(lp133
VNow, the fundamental basis of neoclassical economics
p134
aVwould tell you it's irrational to reject a dollar
p135
aVbecause someone you don't know in another room is going to get 99.
p136
aVYet in thousands of trials with American and European and Japanese students,
p137
aVa significant percentage would reject any offer that's not close to 50/50.
p138
aVAnd although they were screened and didn't know about the game
p139
aVand had never played the game before,
p140
aVproposers seemed to innately know this
p141
aVbecause the average proposal was surprisingly close to 50/50.
p142
aa(lp143
VNow, the interesting part comes in more recently
p144
aVwhen anthropologists began taking this game to other cultures
p145
aVand discovered, to their surprise,
p146
aVthat slash-and-burn agriculturalists in the Amazon
p147
aVor nomadic pastoralists in Central Asia or a dozen different cultures \u2014
p148
aVeach had radically different ideas of what is fair.
p149
aVWhich suggests that instead of there being an innate sense of fairness,
p150
aVthat somehow the basis of our economic
p151
aVtransactions can be influenced by our social institutions,
p152
aVwhether we know that or not.
p153
aa(lp154
VThe other major narrative of social dilemmas is the tragedy of the commons.
p155
aVGarrett Hardin used it to talk about overpopulation in the late 1960s.
p156
aVHe used the example of a common grazing area in which each person
p157
aVby simply maximizing their own flock
p158
aVled to overgrazing and the depletion of the resource.
p159
aVHe had the rather gloomy conclusion that
p160
aVhumans will inevitably despoil any common pool resource
p161
aVin which people cannot be restrained from using it.
p162
aa(lp163
VNow, Elinor Ostrom, a political scientist, in
p164
aV1990 asked the interesting question that any good scientist should ask,
p165
aVwhich is: is it really true that humans will always despoil commons?
p166
aVSo she went out and looked at what data she could find.
p167
aVShe looked at thousands of cases of humans sharing watersheds,
p168
aVforestry resources, fisheries, and discovered that yes, in case after case,
p169
aVhumans destroyed the commons that they depended on.
p170
aVBut she also found many instances in which people escaped the prisoner's dilemma;
p171
aVin fact, the tragedy of the commons is a multiplayer prisoner's dilemma.
p172
aVAnd she said that people are only prisoners if they consider themselves to be.
p173
aVThey escape by creating institutions for collective action.
p174
aVAnd she discovered, I think most interestingly,
p175
aVthat among those institutions that worked,
p176
aVthere were a number of common design
p177
aVprinciples, and those principles seem to be
p178
aVmissing from those institutions that don't work.
p179
